59
00:04:48,090 --> 00:04:50,013
<i>They feel that in you.</i>

60
00:04:51,170 --> 00:04:53,411
<i>My name is James Hunt.</i>

61
00:04:53,530 --> 00:04:55,569
<i>My father is a stockbroker,</i>

62
00:04:55,570 --> 00:04:59,177
<i>my sister is a barrister
and my brother is an accountant.</i>

63
00:05:00,250 --> 00:05:01,695
<i>And I...</i>

64
00:05:02,210 --> 00:05:03,860
<i>Well, I do this.</i>

65
00:05:05,370 --> 00:05:06,895
<i>It's a wonderful way to live.</i>

66
00:05:07,050 --> 00:05:09,098
<i>It's the only way to drive.</i>

67
00:05:10,050 --> 00:05:12,451
<i>As if each day is your last.</i>

68
00:05:21,730 --> 00:05:24,289
I've never been to a Grand Prix before.

69
00:05:24,290 --> 00:05:26,209
Oh, you still haven't.

70
00:05:26,210 --> 00:05:28,736
- This is Formula 3.
- What's that?

71
00:05:29,570 --> 00:05:31,889
It's a lower division,

72
00:05:31,890 --> 00:05:34,416
where idiots like me mess about

73
00:05:34,810 --> 00:05:37,569
in the hope of being talent-spotted
to race in Formula 1.

74
00:05:37,570 --> 00:05:39,572
- You look disappointed.
- No.

75
00:05:40,050 --> 00:05:43,329
Ah. You only slept with me
because you thought I was famous.

76
00:05:43,330 --> 00:05:44,900
That's not true.

77
00:05:45,570 --> 00:05:47,649
Don't worry. I will be one day.

78
00:05:47,650 --> 00:05:49,289
Morning, everyone.

79
00:05:49,290 --> 00:05:50,894
- This is Nursie.
- Gemma.

80
00:05:51,570 --> 00:05:54,489
Nursie, this is Bubbles Horsley,
team manager.

81
00:05:54,490 --> 00:05:55,571
How do you do?

82
00:05:55,970 --> 00:05:57,769
- Bubbles?
- Yeah.

83
00:05:57,770 --> 00:06:00,849
- Doc Postlethwaite, our designer.
- How do you do?

84
00:06:00,850 --> 00:06:04,775
And Alexander, Lord Hesketh,
the team's owner.

85
00:06:05,810 --> 00:06:07,300
How do you do?

86
00:06:08,130 --> 00:06:09,649
Fine, thanks.

87
00:06:09,650 --> 00:06:11,609
Well done, Superstar.

88
00:06:11,610 --> 00:06:14,136
- That's the car?
- Yep, that's her.

89
00:06:14,250 --> 00:06:15,979
Lotus 59.

90
00:06:16,090 --> 00:06:18,821
1,000cc Cosworth MAE engine.

91
00:06:18,930 --> 00:06:21,774
She's no beauty,
but goes like the clappers.

92
00:06:27,865 --> 00:06:30,449
Nothing to be worried about.
Does it before every race.

93
00:06:30,450 --> 00:06:32,609
Good sign, actually. Means he's stoked.

94
00:06:32,610 --> 00:06:36,820
<i>All Formula 3 cars
to the assembly area now, please.</i>

95
00:06:48,530 --> 00:06:51,739
<i>...drivers please bring them
to the scrutineering bay now.</i>

96
00:06:52,130 --> 00:06:53,700
All right, Superstar?

97
00:06:53,810 --> 00:06:55,529
Never better, patron.

98
00:06:55,530 --> 00:06:58,010
- Have a gargle with this.
- Thank you.

99
00:06:59,490 --> 00:07:00,901
Quick toke of this.

100
00:07:01,810 --> 00:07:04,700
<i>At Crystal Palace today,
James Hunt's on pole,</i>

101
00:07:05,530 --> 00:07:08,849
<i>with Austrian newcomer
Niki Lauda alongside him</i>

102
00:07:08,850 --> 00:07:11,569
<i>and Dave Walker completing Row 1.</i>

103
00:07:11,570 --> 00:07:14,050
<i>Row 2 is Mike Beuttler and Dave Morgan,</i>

104
00:07:14,170 --> 00:07:17,060
<i>- with Tony Trimmer and Gerry Birrell.</i>
- Who's that?

105
00:07:17,410 --> 00:07:18,935
He's new.

106
00:07:19,410 --> 00:07:22,329
- Some German.
- Austrian.

107
00:07:22,330 --> 00:07:25,489
He's been here since 5:00 am,
walking the track.

108
00:07:25,490 --> 00:07:27,929
You might actually
have to concentrate today, James.

109
00:07:27,930 --> 00:07:29,534
You'll need these.

110
00:07:30,210 --> 00:07:32,849
Okay, start her up.

111
00:07:32,850 --> 00:07:35,369
Ah! What music!

112
00:07:35,370 --> 00:07:36,929
They could never have imagined it,

113
00:07:36,930 --> 00:07:39,217
those pioneers
who invented the automobile,

114
00:07:39,330 --> 00:07:43,540
that it would possess us like this,
in our imaginations, in our dreams.

115
00:07:44,290 --> 00:07:46,577
Nursie, men love women,

116
00:07:46,690 --> 00:07:48,529
but even more than that,

117
00:07:48,530 --> 00:07:51,852
men love cars.

118
00:07:58,970 --> 00:08:02,133
- Come on, James!
- James! Come on, James!

119
00:08:03,130 --> 00:08:04,541
Go, James!

120
00:08:12,210 --> 00:08:13,449
<i>Hunt's still in the lead,</i>

121
00:08:13,450 --> 00:08:15,612
<i>but Niki Lauda is right on his tail.</i>

122
00:08:24,265 --> 00:08:27,289
<i>Hunt and Lauda are
proving to be in a class of their own.</i>

123
00:08:27,290 --> 00:08:28,894
<i>They're leaving the pack far behind.</i>

124
00:08:29,290 --> 00:08:30,894
<i>Herr</i> Red Devil's on his tail.

125
00:08:36,864 --> 00:08:39,089
<i>Lauda takes
a look down the inside...</i>

126
00:08:40,650 --> 00:08:42,414
<i>...and he's sold him a dummy!</i>

127
00:08:45,930 --> 00:08:47,932
<i>Lauda is through! He's in the lead!</i>

128
00:08:48,770 --> 00:08:51,171
<i>Hunt will be determined
to make up for that mistake.</i>

129
00:08:57,930 --> 00:08:59,500
<i>Hunt's in Lauda's slipstream.</i>

130
00:08:59,610 --> 00:09:01,578
<i>Lauda's not leaving any gap.</i>

131
00:09:06,690 --> 00:09:10,695
<i>The Lotus goes for the inside.
It's an aggressive move from Hunt.</i>

132
00:09:14,770 --> 00:09:16,769
<i>Oh! There's contact!</i>

133
00:09:23,450 --> 00:09:26,693
<i>The leaders have spun out!
Lauda's facing the wrong way!</i>

134
00:09:27,290 --> 00:09:29,657
<i>The back marker's gone through.</i>

135
00:09:29,864 --> 00:09:31,689
<i>You can see why Hunt's fellow drivers</i>

136
00:09:31,690 --> 00:09:33,499
<i>call him "Hunt the Shunt".</i>

137
00:09:36,970 --> 00:09:38,049
Asshole!

138
00:09:38,050 --> 00:09:39,814
- Go on, James!
- The Kraut's out of it.

139
00:09:40,130 --> 00:09:42,129
<i>Lauda is clearly furious.</i>

140
00:09:42,130 --> 00:09:45,649
<i>There's every reason
to expect sharp words in the pits.</i>

141
00:09:45,650 --> 00:09:47,539
<i>It's gonna be victory for Hunt.</i>

142
00:09:47,650 --> 00:09:51,009
<i>It's gonna be an ignominious defeat
for Niki Lauda.</i>

143
00:09:55,690 --> 00:09:59,649
<i>So James Hunt scores his
third major Formula 3 win of the season</i>

144
00:09:59,650 --> 00:10:00,890
<i>here at Crystal Palace,</i>

145
00:10:01,010 --> 00:10:03,809
<i>after a desperate battle
with Niki Lauda.</i>

146
00:10:03,810 --> 00:10:05,539
<i>Lauda was unable to restart</i>

147
00:10:05,650 --> 00:10:08,381
<i>after Hunt's aggressive move
caused them both to spin out</i>

148
00:10:08,490 --> 00:10:09,651
<i>in the last lap of the race.</i>

149
00:10:11,090 --> 00:10:12,770
Hard luck.
Better luck next time.

150
00:10:13,330 --> 00:10:14,855
Hey, asshole.

151
00:10:15,930 --> 00:10:18,169
That was my line. I had that corner.

152
00:10:18,170 --> 00:10:21,413
Do you mean the one that you spun out of
and finished facing the other way?

153
00:10:21,530 --> 00:10:23,929
I think that corner had you.

154
00:10:23,930 --> 00:10:26,529
That move was total suicide.
What if I hadn't braked?

155
00:10:26,530 --> 00:10:29,409
- We'd have crashed.
- But we didn't, did we?

156
00:10:29,410 --> 00:10:31,378
Thanks to your impeccable
survival instincts.

157
00:10:33,530 --> 00:10:35,373
Fuck you. What's your name?

158
00:10:37,010 --> 00:10:41,424
James Simon Wallis Hunt.
Remember it, my little Jerry friend.

159
00:10:41,425 --> 00:10:43,409
<i>Jawohl.</i> Remember ze name.

160
00:10:43,410 --> 00:10:46,249
And it's very simple. Hunt.
It rhymes with...

161
00:10:46,250 --> 00:10:47,449
...cunt.

162
00:10:47,450 --> 00:10:49,930
A word that happens
to describe you perfectly!

163
00:10:50,530 --> 00:10:52,049
Who was that?

164
00:10:52,050 --> 00:10:54,289
I've no idea.
He looks like a rat, doesn't he?

165
00:10:56,530 --> 00:10:57,975
<i>In my home town, Vienna,</i>

166
00:10:58,410 --> 00:11:01,732
<i>my family is famous
for one thing - business.</i>

167
00:11:02,290 --> 00:11:04,577
<i>My grandfather was a businessman,</i>

168
00:11:05,050 --> 00:11:06,495
<i>my father, too.</i>

169
00:11:07,290 --> 00:11:10,489
<i>So when they heard I wanted
to race cars for a living,</i>

170
00:11:10,490 --> 00:11:12,299
<i>they had a few things to say.</i>

171
00:11:12,570 --> 00:11:14,140
<i>Never!</i>

172
00:11:14,807 --> 00:11:17,427
<i>Racing is for playboys and dilettantes.</i>

173
00:11:17,637 --> 00:11:20,227
<i>Frivolous amateurs
with nothing in their heads.</i>

174
00:11:20,767 --> 00:11:22,557
<i>The name Lauda...</i>

175
00:11:22,937 --> 00:11:25,567
<i>belongs with politicians and economists,</i>

176
00:11:26,067 --> 00:11:27,567
<i>on the front pages.</i>

177
00:11:28,027 --> 00:11:30,067
<i>What if this is all I can do?</i>

178
00:11:30,357 --> 00:11:33,157
<i>Then you need my money
more than ever,</i>

179
00:11:33,617 --> 00:11:36,447
<i>so do as I say and follow me
into the family business.</i>

180
00:11:37,410 --> 00:11:38,775
<i>Gut.</i>

181
00:11:42,497 --> 00:11:44,377
<i>Keep your money.</i>

182
00:11:44,707 --> 00:11:46,667
<i>Don't invest in me.</i>

183
00:11:47,007 --> 00:11:49,297
<i>But when I'm world champion</i>

184
00:11:49,667 --> 00:11:52,337
<i>and my name is on the front pages too...</i>

185
00:11:52,677 --> 00:11:54,427
<i>you will regret it.</i>

186
00:11:55,610 --> 00:11:58,341
<i>Get out and never show your face again!</i>

187
00:11:59,450 --> 00:12:01,452
<i>So if my family
wasn't going to help me,</i>

188
00:12:01,610 --> 00:12:05,369
<i>I decided to risk everything
and take out a loan myself.</i>

189
00:12:05,370 --> 00:12:08,340
<i>I found a Formula 1 team
with an okay car</i>

190
00:12:08,450 --> 00:12:10,498
<i>and an owner who had run out of money</i>

191
00:12:10,610 --> 00:12:12,772
<i>and was willing to accept my terms.</i>

192
00:12:13,170 --> 00:12:14,854
And so,
ladies and gentlemen,

193
00:12:14,970 --> 00:12:16,809
I'm delighted to say

194
00:12:16,810 --> 00:12:20,337
that the winner of the Guild of Motoring
Writers Award Driver of the Year...

195
00:12:21,530 --> 00:12:22,531
is James Hunt.

196
00:12:26,450 --> 00:12:27,895
Superb news!

197
00:12:28,650 --> 00:12:30,812
- Well done, James.
- Superstar!

198
00:12:30,970 --> 00:12:32,415
Fantastic!

199
00:12:33,905 --> 00:12:36,329
Well done. Congratulations.
Thank you so much.

200
00:12:36,330 --> 00:12:37,489
Yes!

201
00:12:37,490 --> 00:12:38,849
Erm...

202
00:12:38,850 --> 00:12:41,660
You know, my parents
always wanted me to be a doctor...

203
00:12:41,810 --> 00:12:43,969
...or a stockbroker or something.

204
00:12:43,970 --> 00:12:45,729
They gave me the first-class education,

205
00:12:45,730 --> 00:12:47,889
but, well, that all went terribly wrong

206
00:12:47,890 --> 00:12:49,770
and I ended up with you lot.

207
00:12:52,730 --> 00:12:54,329
Thank you. I need it more than you do.

208
00:12:56,370 --> 00:13:00,056
I mean, I have a hot head,
an inability to tolerate discipline.

209
00:13:00,170 --> 00:13:01,535
- Yes!
- Very true.

210
00:13:02,250 --> 00:13:04,093
I fall out with people left and right.

211
00:13:04,730 --> 00:13:07,849
The only creatures I've ever really
loved or have treated honourably

212
00:13:07,850 --> 00:13:09,852
are budgerigars.

213
00:13:11,170 --> 00:13:15,175
So in any normal area of life I'd be...
or I am, a total liability.

214
00:13:15,530 --> 00:13:17,850
The only thing I've got going for me
is I'm quick in a car.

215
00:13:18,010 --> 00:13:20,009
So, thank you for this
and for acknowledging that.

216
00:13:20,010 --> 00:13:21,529
I'm going to give it to my father

217
00:13:21,530 --> 00:13:23,369
and tell him to put it
on the mantelpiece

218
00:13:23,370 --> 00:13:25,769
and imagine it's a first-class degree
in medicine.

219
00:13:41,050 --> 00:13:42,929
Well done, Superstar.

220
00:13:42,930 --> 00:13:45,536
Another season like that
and I'll move you up to the big time.

221
00:13:45,650 --> 00:13:47,289
Come on, you don't think I'm ready now?

222
00:13:47,290 --> 00:13:50,658
You are. I'm not.
I've got to find you a car first.

223
00:13:50,810 --> 00:13:53,209
Well, go on, then. Chop-chop.

224
00:13:53,210 --> 00:13:55,569
Don't wait too long. You don't want him
to do what Lauda just did.

225
00:13:55,570 --> 00:13:58,609
- Why? What did he do?
- Got himself a drive with BRM.

226
00:13:58,610 --> 00:14:00,889
Well, how the hell did he do that?
He's a nobody.

227
00:14:00,890 --> 00:14:02,409
He's never won a bloody thing.

228
00:14:02,410 --> 00:14:04,409
Apparently, took out a loan
and bought his way in

229
00:14:04,410 --> 00:14:06,129
with two million Austrian schillings.

230
00:14:06,130 --> 00:14:07,575
Jesus.

231
00:14:27,090 --> 00:14:30,139
Niki Lauda.
Here for pre-season testing. BRM?

232
00:14:31,650 --> 00:14:34,460
Sign the release form.
I'll let them know you're here.

233
00:14:46,210 --> 00:14:47,769
- Mr Stanley.
- Good morning.

234
00:14:47,770 --> 00:14:50,769
- Good morning.
- Good morning. Clay!

235
00:14:50,770 --> 00:14:53,529
Let me introduce you
to our number-one driver,

236
00:14:53,530 --> 00:14:55,532
Clay Regazzoni.

237
00:14:56,930 --> 00:14:58,659
- How are you?
- Good.

238
00:14:59,410 --> 00:15:02,414
- Pleasure.
- And these are your mechanics.

239
00:15:02,970 --> 00:15:07,489
They're reporting exclusively to you,
as per contract.

240
00:15:07,490 --> 00:15:09,329
Pleasure. Do you wanna see the car?

241
00:15:09,330 --> 00:15:10,775
Sure.

242
00:15:12,810 --> 00:15:14,221
Hello.

243
00:15:19,250 --> 00:15:21,696
There she is. P160.

244
00:15:22,570 --> 00:15:25,096
- Same as Regazzoni's?
- Identical in every detail.

245
00:15:26,050 --> 00:15:27,540
How much does she weigh?

246
00:15:27,690 --> 00:15:30,296
- 600 kilos.
- But that's crazy.

247
00:15:30,490 --> 00:15:33,169
- Why so heavy?
- It's a V12 engine.

248
00:15:33,170 --> 00:15:36,369
That lump weighs 190K on its own.

249
00:15:36,370 --> 00:15:38,369
Okay.

250
00:15:38,370 --> 00:15:40,729
What horsepower are you getting? 490?

251
00:15:40,730 --> 00:15:43,209
- No, no, 450.
- Well, it's not enough.

252
00:15:43,210 --> 00:15:44,689
It needs to be 500,

253
00:15:44,690 --> 00:15:46,449
and the engine
needs to be 20 kilo lighter.

254
00:15:46,450 --> 00:15:47,769
We already tried.

255
00:15:47,770 --> 00:15:48,931
- Tried what?
- Everything.

256
00:15:49,130 --> 00:15:50,689
We replaced the entire exhaust system.

257
00:15:50,690 --> 00:15:53,978
- Barely made a difference.
- Are you using magnesium parts?

258
00:16:07,010 --> 00:16:08,529
Now the engine block.

259
00:16:08,530 --> 00:16:11,261
Any mounting or fixing plates,
strip it out also.

260
00:16:11,570 --> 00:16:14,729
When you've done that,
we have to look at the aerodynamics,

261
00:16:14,730 --> 00:16:16,494
front and rear wing.

262
00:16:33,930 --> 00:16:36,012
Okay, thank you. Good night.

263
00:16:55,970 --> 00:16:57,415
What was Regazzoni's time?

264
00:16:59,290 --> 00:17:00,701
1:53.

265
00:17:01,050 --> 00:17:03,969
Okay, now put him in my car,
and he'll go round two seconds faster.

266
00:17:03,970 --> 00:17:07,019
- Well, that's impossible.
- No chance.

267
00:17:10,050 --> 00:17:12,409
We've been
working on it all night.

268
00:17:12,410 --> 00:17:14,529
Put Regazzoni in the car.
See what happens.

269
00:17:14,530 --> 00:17:16,449
I don't understand.
Why am I supposed to do this?

270
00:17:16,450 --> 00:17:18,449
I don't know, Clay.
He just wants you to take it for a spin.

271
00:17:21,650 --> 00:17:23,249
Gloves, please.

272
00:17:23,250 --> 00:17:24,695
<i>'fanculo.</i>

273
00:18:07,890 --> 00:18:11,009
- I would say we push it a bit...
- All right.

274
00:18:11,010 --> 00:18:13,089
What did you do to the car?

275
00:18:13,090 --> 00:18:16,617
That's information I will share with you
under certain conditions only.

276
00:18:16,850 --> 00:18:18,295
Go on.

277
00:18:19,370 --> 00:18:21,054
A guaranteed place in the team,

278
00:18:21,410 --> 00:18:23,930
and a paid contract on equal terms
with Regazzoni for two years.

279
00:18:25,170 --> 00:18:26,774
Are you crazy?

280
00:18:26,890 --> 00:18:30,417
Clay's a senior figure in Formula 1.
You're just a rookie.

281
00:18:30,770 --> 00:18:33,330
Well, the only reason we took you on
is because you're paying us.

282
00:18:33,610 --> 00:18:36,929
Well, as of now, if you want me to stay,
we rip up the contract.

283
00:18:36,930 --> 00:18:39,661
- I don't pay you a cent.
- That's outrageous!

284
00:18:40,170 --> 00:18:42,252
Was he quicker in my car?

285
00:18:42,970 --> 00:18:44,972
He was, wasn't he?

286
00:18:45,690 --> 00:18:47,931
Did he go two seconds faster?

287
00:18:51,570 --> 00:18:53,015
2.3.

288
00:18:55,730 --> 00:18:57,858
So, have a think,

289
00:18:58,490 --> 00:19:00,731
work out your priorities
and get back to me.

290
00:19:15,730 --> 00:19:17,141
Hey, Niki.

291
00:19:19,530 --> 00:19:22,420
I know what you're going to say,
that it's none of my business.

292
00:19:22,530 --> 00:19:23,531
What?

293
00:19:24,930 --> 00:19:28,252
If it's the track manager
you're taking on your date tonight...

294
00:19:29,290 --> 00:19:30,929
It's none of your business.

295
00:19:30,930 --> 00:19:34,696
Okay, but if you want my advice,
I'd let this one go.

296
00:19:36,050 --> 00:19:39,691
I'm not questioning your taste.
She is a great girl, but...

297
00:19:41,330 --> 00:19:45,289
Agnes's last boyfriend
was a British Formula 2 driver

298
00:19:45,290 --> 00:19:47,689
who has a reputation for two things.

299
00:19:47,690 --> 00:19:50,375
For being a little crazy on the track,

300
00:19:50,530 --> 00:19:54,694
and for going all night and all day
and all night again in bed.

301
00:19:54,810 --> 00:19:58,329
He's a good driver,
but an immortal fuck, apparently.

302
00:19:58,330 --> 00:20:01,369
I don't know about you, but
that's not an act I'd like to follow.

303
00:20:04,610 --> 00:20:06,692
But if that doesn't bother you...

304
00:20:08,610 --> 00:20:11,580
What's his name, the driver?

305
00:20:11,810 --> 00:20:13,335
Hunt. James Hunt.

306
00:20:17,450 --> 00:20:20,897
You see, you share information
and I share information.

307
00:20:22,250 --> 00:20:24,457
That's what teammates are for.

308
00:20:34,690 --> 00:20:36,249
<i>Where the hell are we going?</i>

309
00:20:36,250 --> 00:20:38,609
<i>I promise
it'll be worth it.</i>

310
00:20:38,610 --> 00:20:40,055
<i>Just keep them closed.</i>

311
00:20:40,490 --> 00:20:41,935
Wait for it.

312
00:20:42,770 --> 00:20:44,579
Wait for it.

313
00:20:47,930 --> 00:20:50,376
There. What do you say?

314
00:20:50,490 --> 00:20:52,060
She's Formula 1.

315
00:20:52,490 --> 00:20:54,174
Yes, she is, Superstar.

316
00:20:54,610 --> 00:20:57,489
Your brother and I got together
with the bean counters.

317
00:20:57,490 --> 00:20:58,969
And since the economics of F1

318
00:20:58,970 --> 00:21:02,609
are not so significantly different
to the economics of Formula 2,

319
00:21:02,610 --> 00:21:05,011
well, we thought if we were
going to be losing money,

320
00:21:05,130 --> 00:21:08,249
we might as well be doing it on
the big roulette table in Formula 1.

321
00:21:08,250 --> 00:21:11,572
You fat, little, inbred beauty.
Come here.

322
00:21:15,890 --> 00:21:19,212
Actually, credit where it's due,
we got the idea from Niki.

323
00:21:19,490 --> 00:21:21,489
- Who?
- Lauda.

324
00:21:21,490 --> 00:21:24,329
Bought his way in, rather than
mess about in the lower divisions.

325
00:21:24,330 --> 00:21:25,900
I thought, "Bloody hell, he's right."

326
00:21:26,130 --> 00:21:29,609
No sponsorship, Superstar.
I hope you approve.

327
00:21:29,610 --> 00:21:33,615
No vulgar logos
for cigarettes or condoms.

328
00:21:34,170 --> 00:21:36,218
Just plain white with the flags. Ooh!

329
00:21:36,650 --> 00:21:39,620
And racing overalls which read,

330
00:21:40,810 --> 00:21:43,409
"Sex. Breakfast of champions."

331
00:21:46,090 --> 00:21:47,899
So, when do we start?

332
00:21:48,850 --> 00:21:51,057
- Soon as you're ready.
- Ready?

333
00:21:51,370 --> 00:21:53,941
I've been waiting for this
my whole life.

334
00:22:02,930 --> 00:22:04,969
- Hi, welcome to Watkins Glen.
- Hello!

335
00:22:04,970 --> 00:22:06,734
<i>When the season started,
people wondered</i>

336
00:22:07,050 --> 00:22:09,860
<i>whether Lord Hesketh and his team
of upper-class enthusiasts</i>

337
00:22:10,210 --> 00:22:14,689
<i>were bringing glamour
to the racing community, or just comedy.</i>

338
00:22:14,690 --> 00:22:16,849
Certainly, it was the first time
anyone had seen

339
00:22:16,850 --> 00:22:20,489
a butler serving oysters and caviar
in the pits.

340
00:22:20,490 --> 00:22:23,329
But they have made quite an impact.

341
00:22:23,330 --> 00:22:26,569
Sixth in France, fourth in Britain
and third in Holland.

342
00:22:26,570 --> 00:22:30,249
<i>All drivers on the track,
caution flags are out.</i>

343
00:22:30,250 --> 00:22:32,424
<i>A severe crash at the Esses.</i>

344
00:22:32,425 --> 00:22:34,529
<i>Red flag.
There is a car off the track.</i>

345
00:22:34,530 --> 00:22:36,289
And reports are reaching me

346
00:22:36,290 --> 00:22:38,497
that there has been
a serious accident in qualifying.

347
00:22:38,704 --> 00:22:41,449
Er, the identity of the driver we don't
currently have at the moment,

348
00:22:41,450 --> 00:22:43,657
but, as you can tell
from all the activity

349
00:22:43,770 --> 00:22:45,449
going on behind me towards the track,

350
00:22:45,450 --> 00:22:47,929
it is clearly a grave incident indeed.

351
00:22:47,930 --> 00:22:49,409
We will, of course,
have more information for you

352
00:22:49,410 --> 00:22:50,457
as and when we get it,

353
00:22:50,570 --> 00:22:54,575
but it is the sight and sound
of Formula 1 nobody likes to see.

354
00:22:58,570 --> 00:23:00,334
- Get your hands off me.
- Hey, come on.

355
00:23:10,265 --> 00:23:11,929
<i>Drivers of top stature</i>

356
00:23:11,930 --> 00:23:13,729
<i>we've lost just in the past four seasons</i>

357
00:23:13,730 --> 00:23:18,649
<i>have included Piers Courage,
Jochen Rindt,</i>

358
00:23:18,650 --> 00:23:22,009
<i>Jo Siffert, Roger Williamson</i>

359
00:23:22,010 --> 00:23:24,289
<i>and today, at Watkins Glen,</i>

360
00:23:24,290 --> 00:23:26,611
<i>Formula 1 has claimed another driver.</i>

361
00:23:27,210 --> 00:23:29,497
<i>The Tyrrell team
have withdrawn from the race.</i>

362
00:23:29,610 --> 00:23:32,329
<i>Their places on the grid
will be left empty.</i>

363
00:23:32,330 --> 00:23:34,776
- Terrible.
- They should cancel the race.

364
00:23:35,010 --> 00:23:36,535
Why?

365
00:23:36,850 --> 00:23:39,296
He made a mistake,
went into the corner too fast.

366
00:23:39,410 --> 00:23:40,889
It's his fault.

367
00:23:40,890 --> 00:23:42,779
- Is that right?
- It's obvious.

368
00:23:43,170 --> 00:23:44,899
Look at the tyre marks.

369
00:23:45,290 --> 00:23:48,609
So says the nobody
who had to pay for his own drive.

370
00:23:48,610 --> 00:23:50,290
How's that working out for you,
by the way?

371
00:23:50,490 --> 00:23:53,300
Fine. How is it at the back?

372
00:23:54,210 --> 00:23:56,292
Not planning on being there for long.

373
00:23:57,065 --> 00:23:58,769
<i>Ten minutes to the warm-up lap.</i>

374
00:23:58,770 --> 00:24:00,289
<i>Ten minutes.</i>

375
00:24:00,290 --> 00:24:01,621
<i>Asshole.</i>

376
00:24:03,610 --> 00:24:04,975
Arsehole.

377
00:24:06,370 --> 00:24:09,729
<i>Heading into
the Grand Hotel hairpin, second gear.</i>

378
00:24:09,730 --> 00:24:10,809
Turn in hard,

379
00:24:10,810 --> 00:24:13,461
looking for late apex,
gentle with the bar.

380
00:24:15,210 --> 00:24:18,339
Heading into Portier, second gear,
clip the apex,

381
00:24:18,450 --> 00:24:22,011
light brake, stay in second,
looking for a good exit.

382
00:24:22,370 --> 00:24:24,489
Heading through the tunnel,
gradual right,

383
00:24:24,490 --> 00:24:27,529
up through third, fourth, fifth...

384
00:24:27,530 --> 00:24:29,532
Is Alexander round?

385
00:24:30,050 --> 00:24:32,729
Er, yes, he was.

386
00:24:32,730 --> 00:24:34,409
He went back to the house
to take a call.

387
00:24:34,410 --> 00:24:36,249
He'll be back shortly.

388
00:24:36,250 --> 00:24:38,412
He only wanted to show me
his pride and joy.

389
00:24:39,370 --> 00:24:42,169
Rhymes with "boy", if you ask me.

390
00:24:42,170 --> 00:24:44,049
And "toy".

391
00:24:44,050 --> 00:24:48,329
God, it's so flimsy
for something that costs so much.

392
00:24:48,330 --> 00:24:52,409
There's no comfort,
no protection, nothing.

393
00:24:52,410 --> 00:24:55,129
No, it's just a little coffin, really.

394
00:24:55,130 --> 00:24:58,249
Surrounded by high-octane fuel in here.

395
00:24:58,250 --> 00:25:01,249
Being driven round 170 miles per hour.

396
00:25:01,250 --> 00:25:04,413
To all intents and purposes,
this thing's a bomb on wheels.

397
00:25:05,570 --> 00:25:07,493
You're James, aren't you?

398
00:25:08,730 --> 00:25:10,220
Yes.

399
00:25:11,170 --> 00:25:12,899
You fit the description.

400
00:25:13,290 --> 00:25:14,701
Is that right?

401
00:25:15,930 --> 00:25:17,898
Suzy. Friend of Alex's.

402
00:25:18,010 --> 00:25:21,139
Yeah, yeah. I know exactly.

403
00:25:22,810 --> 00:25:24,369
What was the description?

404
00:25:24,370 --> 00:25:25,969
Mostly positive,
in terms of appearance.

405
00:25:25,970 --> 00:25:28,177
Negative only in terms of character.

406
00:25:28,690 --> 00:25:30,613
I've been told to avoid you.

407
00:25:31,010 --> 00:25:32,421
By whom?

408
00:25:32,850 --> 00:25:35,769
Alexander. He says you're a bad boy.

409
00:25:35,770 --> 00:25:38,129
Alexander doesn't know
what he's talking about.

410
00:25:38,130 --> 00:25:40,569
I was. I'm not any more.

411
00:25:40,570 --> 00:25:44,169
The new me is very professional.
Early to bed, early to rise.

412
00:25:44,170 --> 00:25:45,809
- All very dull.
- Hmm.

413
00:25:45,810 --> 00:25:47,249
But according to the team,

414
00:25:47,250 --> 00:25:49,931
"The best way to
keep beating the goose-stepper."

415
00:25:50,625 --> 00:25:52,329
Is that what you were doing
when I came in?

416
00:25:52,330 --> 00:25:55,369
Yes, visualisation techniques,
memorising the circuit,

417
00:25:55,370 --> 00:25:58,055
in this case Monaco, which is up next.

418
00:26:02,850 --> 00:26:06,089
Personally, I've always been a great
believer in getting there on the day,

419
00:26:06,090 --> 00:26:08,649
putting my foot down
and playing chicken with everyone else.

420
00:26:10,705 --> 00:26:12,409
But they don't want me
doing that any more.

421
00:26:12,410 --> 00:26:16,495
They want my body like a temple
and my mind like a monk.

422
00:26:17,170 --> 00:26:20,369
And what about your soul, your heart?

423
00:26:20,370 --> 00:26:22,609
Well, they've got ideas about that, too.

424
00:26:22,610 --> 00:26:25,209
They want me to stop messing around,
settle down,

425
00:26:25,210 --> 00:26:27,529
get married
with the next nice girl I meet.

426
00:26:27,530 --> 00:26:28,941
They think it would be good for me.

427
00:26:29,410 --> 00:26:31,412
Hmm. What do you think?

428
00:26:31,770 --> 00:26:35,092
It sounds fucking awful.

429
00:26:36,210 --> 00:26:38,577
But since they're right
about most things,

430
00:26:38,850 --> 00:26:41,569
- they're probably right about that, too.
- Hmm.

431
00:26:41,570 --> 00:26:43,971
You don't fancy getting married, do you?

432
00:27:09,370 --> 00:27:10,895
Suzy.

433
00:27:11,610 --> 00:27:13,021
Bravo!

434
00:27:13,370 --> 00:27:15,293
Hey, hey, hey!

435
00:27:18,850 --> 00:27:20,773
- What's going on with him?
- Nothing. Nothing.

436
00:27:21,130 --> 00:27:22,541
Didn't want to ruin your day.

437
00:27:23,130 --> 00:27:25,531
It's... It's the Kraut.

438
00:27:25,810 --> 00:27:27,380
What about him?

439
00:27:28,250 --> 00:27:30,169
He's just been signed by Ferrari.

440
00:27:30,170 --> 00:27:33,891
You're kidding me?
Jesus. How did that happen?

441
00:27:34,170 --> 00:27:35,660
Did he buy his way in there, too?

442
00:27:35,770 --> 00:27:41,409
Well, the old man took Regazzoni back
and he insisted on it, apparently.

443
00:27:41,410 --> 00:27:43,378
He says that Niki's a genius
setting up the cars.

444
00:28:02,690 --> 00:28:04,454
It's terrible. Drives like a pig.

445
00:28:05,290 --> 00:28:07,657
- Oh, you can't say that.
- Why not?

446
00:28:08,010 --> 00:28:10,058
- It's a Ferrari!
- It's a shitbox.

447
00:28:10,530 --> 00:28:13,969
It understeers like crazy and
the weight distribution is a disaster.

448
00:28:13,970 --> 00:28:17,019
It's amazing, all these facilities
and you make a piece of crap like this.

449
00:28:18,410 --> 00:28:19,849
Uh!

450
00:28:27,087 --> 00:28:31,087
We are happy
to welcome back to the Ferrari family...

451
00:28:31,427 --> 00:28:33,547
our good friend Clay Regazzoni,

452
00:28:33,927 --> 00:28:35,967
and to introduce Niki Lauda,

453
00:28:36,597 --> 00:28:37,677
from Austria.

454
00:28:48,490 --> 00:28:51,729
"Ferrari family."
"Our good friend Clay Regazzoni."

455
00:28:51,730 --> 00:28:55,289
You are family and friend
to the commendatore as long as you win.

456
00:28:55,290 --> 00:28:56,701
The minute you don't, ciao, ciao.

457
00:28:57,010 --> 00:29:01,140
I totally understand. It's business.
I would do the same.

458
00:29:01,250 --> 00:29:04,249
But it isn't
just business, is it? What we do.

459
00:29:04,250 --> 00:29:06,409
It's passion, love.

460
00:29:06,410 --> 00:29:09,249
Which is why we are prepared
to risk our lives for it.

461
00:29:09,250 --> 00:29:10,369
Not me.

462
00:29:10,370 --> 00:29:13,091
If I had more talent and could earn
better money with something else,

463
00:29:13,250 --> 00:29:14,929
I would.

464
00:29:14,930 --> 00:29:18,609
How do you know you will
make money here? You haven't yet.

465
00:29:18,610 --> 00:29:20,931
Not yet, but I will.

466
00:29:21,610 --> 00:29:23,499
If you can, I can.

467
00:29:27,370 --> 00:29:29,213
You know, are you ever not an asshole?

468
00:29:30,570 --> 00:29:32,609
- Why am I an asshole?
- Well...

469
00:29:32,610 --> 00:29:34,209
You know, by now
I'm both quicker than you

470
00:29:34,210 --> 00:29:36,129
and better at setting up the car.

471
00:29:36,130 --> 00:29:37,969
You can't deal with it,
so you're the asshole.

472
00:29:37,970 --> 00:29:39,131
Screw you.

473
00:29:47,050 --> 00:29:50,329
I brought you along today because
you seem like a lonely kind of guy.

474
00:29:50,330 --> 00:29:52,289
I thought if I introduced you
to some nice people,

475
00:29:52,290 --> 00:29:54,169
that could rub off on you.

476
00:29:54,170 --> 00:29:56,889
Forget it. Make your own friends.

477
00:29:56,890 --> 00:29:59,575
Come on, Clay. I'm sorry.

478
00:30:35,090 --> 00:30:36,535
Are you leaving?

479
00:30:37,650 --> 00:30:39,061
Yes.

480
00:30:39,530 --> 00:30:41,289
Can you give me a lift
to the nearest town,

481
00:30:41,290 --> 00:30:42,735
anywhere with a train station?

